Data Analysis on Stack Overflow( Prepared By Arvind Singh)¶

Stack Overflow is the world largest developer community for online question-and-answer site for programmers where we can find and fix our day to day bugs and errors which we might encounter during our development of software or projects, and ask out for help from developers or Stack Overflow community from anywhere across the world.

what we can do with Stack Overflow:¶

collaboratively tag and edit questions.
vote on the quality of answers.
and post comments on individual questions and answers.

Coming to dataset we will be using Stack Overflow .csv format dataset.
you can get it from here: https://www.ics.uci.edu/~duboisc/stackoverflow/
We will process this data and based on that it will be easy for developer, data scientist and programmers to visualize and get insights of Stack Overflow survey.

This project is done after completing the course. Project is prepared under Data Analyis course, whose instructor is: Aakash N S also a founder of https://www.jovian.ml/

As a first step, let's upload our Jupyter notebook to Jovian.ml.

In [210]:



     


from collections import Counter

# Counter is function and it will return the no... of tags

count_tags = Counter(alltags)
# count_tags now will contains values in the form of (Key, Values)
# where keys will be tags and values will be count of keys.

tags = pd.DataFrame([list(count_tags.keys()), list(count_tags.values())])
tags = tags.transpose()
tags.columns = ['tag', 'count']


# ascending=False help sort function to sort values in descending order

languages_arr = ['jquery', 'python', 'java', 'php', 'c++', 'javascript']
x = []
y = []
for lang in languages_arr:
    index = list(tags['tag']).index(lang)
    x.append(lang)
    y.append(list(tags['count'])[index])

From the table, we can infer following observations:


    

  • A particluar question took a minimum of 26 views to obtain 1 answer.
    • 

  • 25% of the questions took around 98 views to obtain an average of 2 answers.
    • 

  • 50% of the questions took around 172 views to obtain an average of 3 answers.
    • 

  • 75% of the questions took around 310 views to obtain an average of 5 answers.
    • 

  • A particular question took a maximum of 2104 views to obtain total of 23 answers
    •

avg = np.average(time_qa['diff_in_time'])
print("Average of Resoponse time is = ", avg )

# to convert millisecond into second divide by 1000

avg_hr = 133824.02  / 1000

print("Average amount of time taken to answer a question is = ",np.round_(avg), "which is roughly = ", np.round_(avg_hr), "seconds.  or ", np.round_(avg_hr/60), "hours")

In [105]:



     


# let's first make the list of tag
# using only ( tag_rating[tag].append(rating['score_a'][i]) ) might throws Exception

tag_rating = {}
for i in tqdm(range(len(rating['tags']))):
    for tag in rating['tags'][i].split(','):
        try:
            tag_rating[tag].append(rating['score_a'][i])
        except Exception:
            tag_rating[tag] = [rating['score_a'][i]]

Conclusion¶
    

  • Please Note: This Data Analysis is done on dataset between February 18, 2009 and June 7, 2009 downloaded from: https://www.ics.uci.edu/~duboisc/stackoverflow/
    • 



    

  • java is the most popular languages among the selected ['jquery', 'python', 'java', 'php', 'c++', 'javascript']
    • 

  • A particluar question took a minimum of 26 views to obtain 1 answer.
    • 

  • 25% of the questions took around 98 views to obtain an average of 2 answers.
    • 

  • 50% of the questions took around 172 views to obtain an average of 3 answers.
    • 

  • 75% of the questions took around 310 views to obtain an average of 5 answers.
    • 

  • A particular question took a maximum of 2104 views to obtain total of 23 answers
